// Indentation grammar where the *contextual* lexer's state-narrowing is
// load-bearing, exercised together with the Indenter postlex hook (issue #67).
//
// `NAME` and `VALUE` are two distinct regex terminals that match the *same* span
// (`/[a-z]+/`). They never share a parser state — `NAME` starts an `assign` (or
// follows `if`), `VALUE` only appears after `=` — so the contextual lexer lexes
// each correctly by parser state. The *basic* lexer cannot: it always picks
// `NAME` (the tie-break winner), so `x = y` fails because `y` is not a `VALUE`.
//
// This is the case the #41 `indent`/`indent_paren` grammars do NOT cover: there,
// basic and contextual produce identical trees, so replaying them on both lexers
// only checks parity. Here the contextual lexer does work the basic lexer can't,
// *while* INDENT/DEDENT are being injected — pinning that postlex and contextual
// narrowing interact correctly. Generated and run under `lexer='contextual'` only.
start: _NL* stmt+
?stmt: assign | block
assign: NAME "=" VALUE _NL
block: "if" NAME ":" _NL _INDENT stmt+ _DEDENT
NAME: /[a-z]+/
VALUE: /[a-z]+/
_NL: /(\r?\n[ \t]*)+/
%declare _INDENT _DEDENT
%ignore " "
